<!-- By Dependent Issues (Action) - DO NOT REMOVE -->
In principle, the Lean compiler should not use this hypothesis that D is injective unless it is needed, but can you make sure that this is the case?

```lean
@[nolint unusedArguments]
def CharacterModule [Injective <| ModuleCat.of R D] : Type (max uR uM uD) := M â†’â‚—[R] D
```
this should do the trick

I think @AntoineChambert-Loir means that you should only include the injectivity hypothesis when needed, rather than having it as a `variable` (so that readers of the source code (e.g. PR reviewers) can't easily figure out whether injectivity is used or not (even though it's easy to figure out in VSCode or the online docs)).
I suggest that you make this fully universe polymorphic and specialize only when necessary, and replace `CategoryTheory.Injective` by `Module.Injective` here.
This is done, I will see if flatness still works using `R`-linear map later in another branch
L could probably be implicit
done
Male L implicit?
done
Make M implicit? (Same below)
done in [0d454a1](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/8905/commits/0d454a1f2a3935d7066a06fbc7e4b8190557321c)

This one can be defined using `flip` and `llcomp` just like [Module.Dual.transpose](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/Dual.html#Module.Dual.transpose), ~~at least in the commutative case~~ (it doesn't generalize to the noncommutative case; need bimodules). The name could be characterDual in analogy to [LinearMap.dualMap](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/Dual.html#LinearMap.dualMap).

I think `M â†’â‚—[R] D` should not be made a separate definition, because all instances are the same as on the type of linear maps. Also, in the case of Matlis duality, it's not called a character module in the literature.

Only when you get to `A â†’â‚—[â„¤] AddCircle (1 : â„š)` and want to add a non-canonical R-action on the domain do you need to make a new def. So what you currently call `unitRationalCircle` should be called `CharacterModule` instead.
I see, I will split this file and leave `CharacterModule` only to mean `A â†’â‚—[â„¤] AddCircle (1 : â„š)`; and move the rest to other more fitting places. Thanks
This is done now.

As I said, this could be constructed using `flip` and `llcomp` (cf. [Module.Dual.transpose](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/Dual.html#Module.Dual.transpose)) and could go into Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.BilinearMap together with `cong` below (it's usually called `congr`). The next lemma might go into Mathlib.Algebra.Module.Injective. The functor could maybe go into Mathlib.Algebra.Category.ModuleCat.Basic; it's a nice addition even though not what you'd use for flatness.

Only the part about `A â†’â‚—[â„¤] AddCircle (1 : â„š)` should stay in this PR. That was the main content of #8559 while this PR is largely independent of it.
Thanks! I have remove the character module file and moved everything else to more fitting files.

In fact this could also be constructed using arrowCongr so it should be named LinearEquiv.congrLeft in analogy to [LinearEquiv.congrRight](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/Basic.html#LinearEquiv.congrRight).
done
